Do you mean interest in general or interest in regards to this question?

is it like when you give money and then that person gives more money
Not quite. Interest is money that you either pay or receive when you are borrowing or saving money
I may want to borrow Â£500 from the bank
I would have to pay back the Â£500 but they would also charge me interest
which would be a percentage of what I have borrowed
For example they may charge me 10% interest
So in total I would have to pay the bank Â£550 back
That is just one example of interest and you will have to study two different types of interest
Compound interest is where you get interest on the interest
So one year you might save Â£500 and get 10% interest
This means you will have Â£550 saved
You will get 10% of the 500 but also 10% of the interest you got last year
So compound interest is where you will also earn interest on any interest you have previously been given
With simple interest we only get interest on the initial amount we save
So we may save Â£500 and get 10% interest but with simple interest we will keep getting Â£50 interest
no matter how many years we save for

We now need to look at  how we worked out the interest
10% of the amount you saved or you got from the bank

The question does this by turning the 10% into a fraction
q/100 is the percentage as a fraction
and p is the initial amount
p x (q/100) is the interest earned
and if we multiply this by n we get the total amount of interest
